Univariate Numerical Feature Observations:¶

  • No missing or incorrect value shere, numerical features which contain zeros are of such a type that a zero is not an incorrect value.
  • There are no values which seem out of a plausable range.
  • The value most likely to be out of practical range is a value oif 275 for the 'previous' feature, however, it is quite possible that the value could be so high. The fact that it is so high above all of the other values makes it seem false though, but it is only one value and probably won't have much of an effect.
  • There is a lot of data which fallas out of the 25% to 75% range, however these values are still in a reasonable range for the item which they present. Are they then still considered outliers?
  • I don't see a point in capping any of these features or replacing the streme values with mean or mode. since these avalues all represent real world data, the model must learn to deal with them in order to be practical in the real world. Altering this data might make the model more accurate for this dataset, but will result in innaccuracy with new data.
  • Taking the log of the 'duration' feature might distribute it more normally, but would that really achieve anything?

# Look for any relationship between the categorical features and the percentage of successful product subscription.
# Also tak total samples into account beacause data with a low number of samples could be biased.
count=0
for column in bankData.drop(columns=['Target']):
    if (bankData[column].dtype == "object"):
        temp_df = pd.crosstab(bankData[column], bankData["Target"])
        temp_df['Total'] = (temp_df['no'].add(temp_df['yes']))
        temp_df['% Success'] = (round(temp_df['yes'].div(temp_df['no'].add(temp_df['yes']))*100,2))
        temp_df_sorted = temp_df.sort_values(by='% Success', ascending=False)
        print(temp_df_sorted)
        
        f, (ax_per, ax_tot) = plt.subplots(2, gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (.5, .5)}, figsize=(15,8))
        sns.barplot(x=temp_df_sorted.index, y=temp_df_sorted['% Success'], ax=ax_per)
        sns.barplot(x=temp_df_sorted.index, y=temp_df_sorted['Total'], ax=ax_tot)
        ax_per.set_title("Percent Success and Total Samples of "+column, size='x-large')
        ax_per.set_xlabel("")
        ax_per.set_xticklabels(temp_df_sorted.index)
        ax_per.set_ylabel("% Success", size='x-large')
        ax_tot.set_xlabel(column, size='x-large')
        ax_tot.set_xticklabels(temp_df_sorted.index)
        ax_tot.set_ylabel("Total Samples", size='x-large')
        count = 0
        for index, row in temp_df_sorted.iterrows():
            ax_per.text(count, row['% Success'], str(row['% Success'])+'%', color='black', ha="center")
            ax_tot.text(count, row['Total'], str(row['Total']), color='black', ha="center")
            count +=  1
        plt.show()

Categorical Feature Relation to Target¶

  • For some reason students, retirees and unemployed people have the highest success percentages, these are the people who are supposed to have the least amount of money. However, looking at the value counts, these 3 job categories also have relatively low numbers, therefore the high percentages may just be due to the low number of samples.
  • Single people and people with tertiary education show higher percentages of accpeting the offer, this is also interesting because both these categories have mid range value counts within their respective features.
  • People who have not defaulted on debt and people who currently have no debt have a higher percentage of accepting the offer, this is quite obvious, since such people are more likely to have spare money to invest.
  • People who accepted the previous offer are quite likely to accept the new offer.
  • Notice that the months with the highest success percentage are also the months with the lowest number of samples.
  • The rest of the features are quite randomly associated to success percentage.

Success Percentage Among Job Categories¶

  • The retired job category has the highest mean balance and they are at a stage where they need to make safe investments, so it makes sense that they have a high percentage of offer acceptance.
  • The student and unemployed categories have mid-range mean balances, which I would say is quite strange, unless these are trust fund babies and spouses of wealthy people respectively.
  • It is also worthy to note from the univariate analysis that the number of samples form the retired, student and unemployed categories are quite low compared to the total number of samples. Therefore, it may just be sheer chance that the success percentage for these categories are high. One might find that the success percentage drops as the sample numbers for these categories increases.

# First Create some functions which will help the analysis.

# A function to plote the confusion matrix.
def plotConfusionMatrix(model, xTest, yTest):
    yPredict = model.predict(xTest)
    cm=metrics.confusion_matrix(yTest, yPredict)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,  fmt='g', xticklabels = [0,1] , yticklabels = [0,1])
    plt.ylabel('Observed')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()

# A function to plot the yeelowbrick library visulizations.
def plotYellowbrickVis(model, xTrain, xTest, yTrain, yTest):
    classRep = ClassificationReport(model)
    classRep.fit(xTrain, yTrain)
    classRep.score(xTest, yTest)
    classRep.show()

    roc = ROCAUC(model)
    roc.fit(xTrain, yTrain)
    rocScore = roc.score(xTest, yTest)
    roc.show()

# A function to calculate and return all the performance metrics.
def getMetrics(modelName, model, xTrain, xTest, yTrain, yTest):
    ''' Returns a series which can be appended to a dataframe.'''
    yPred = model.predict(xTest)
    metricsDict = {'Train Accuracy':round(model.score(xTrain, yTrain), 4),
                    'Test Accuracy':round(model.score(xTest, yTest), 4),
                    'Recall':round(recall_score(yTest, yPred), 4),
                    'Precision':round(precision_score(yTest, yPred), 4),
                    'F1 Score':round(f1_score(yTest, yPred), 4),
                    'AUC Score':round(roc_auc_score(yTest, yPred), 4)}
    metricsSeries = pd.Series(name=modelName, data=metricsDict)
    return metricsSeries

def appendMetrics(metrics_df, metrics_series, aucMicro, aucMacro):
    metrics_series['AUC Micro'] = aucMicro
    metrics_series['AUC Macro'] = aucMacro
    metrics_df = results_df.append(metrics_series)
    metrics_df.drop_duplicates(inplace=True)
    return metrics_df

Logistic Regression and Decision Tree Observations¶

  • Both models yield very similar results and both have a high accuracy.
  • However, since there is a large class imbalance, the accuracy is misleading and should not be used as the primary metric.
  • We want to miss out on as few actual clients as possible, while cutting down marketing to clients who will not accept.
  • Therefore, I would say that the recall and precision are more important.
  • The higher the recall, the more clients who will actually accept the offer are contacted, therefore increasing revenue.
  • The higher the precision, the fewer clients who will not accept the offer are contacted, therefore decreasing marketing costs.
  • Therefore, both recall and precision are important metrics for this problem.
  • The F1 score reflects how good both precision and acuuracy are combined.
  • Therefore, a high F1 score means that we are acheiving both our goals of increasing revenue and cutting costs.
  • Thus, I would say that F1 score is the most important metric for this application.
  • When F1 scores between models are close, we should weigh potential income to marketing costs and decide which is more important.
  • I would ay that getting a few more clients will generate more revenue than contacting a few more clients would cost.
  • Therefore, for models with close F1 scores, I would take the one with higher recall.
  • Thus Between the above models, I would choose the decision tree.

Conclusion¶

  • The models do not differ greatly from one another.
  • The logistic rgression and the decission tree both did remarkably well considering that they are much simpler models than the ensemble models.
  • Looking at the sum of the metrics, the Gradient Boosting classifier has the best overall performance by a small margin.
  • However, the Random Forest classifier has the highest Recall value.
  • This results in the Random Forest classifier having the highest number of true positives and the lowest number of false negatives.
  • Thus, the Random Forest Classifier will target the highest number of people who accept the offer.
  • Although the Random Forest Classifier does not have the highest Precision value, the precision is comparible to that of the other models.
  • A slightly lower precision value will mean that there will be more unsuccessful marketing attempts than other models would have.
  • However, I believe that the revenue generated by the higher successes will outweigh the costs of the unsuccessful attempts.
  • In Conclusion, the Random Forest classifier is the best model for this business case.
